ity%20that%20they%20might%20lose%20access%20to%20their%20Gmail%20accounts%20in%20the%20upcoming%20month.%20In%20December%202023%2C%20millions%20of%20Gmail%20accounts%20are%20at%20risk%20of%20being%20deleted%20as%20part%20of%20a%20process%20that%20specifically%20aims%20to%20deactivate%20accounts%20that%20have%20remained%20inactive%20for%20a%20minimum%20of%20two%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fblog.google%2Ftechnology%2Fsafety-security%2Fupdating-our-inactive-account-policies%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3Eblog%20post%20%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3Ewritten%20by%20Google%20Vice%20President%20of%20Product%20Management%20Ruth%20Kricheli%20in%20May%2C%20the%20company%20said%20it%20is%20taking%20steps%20to%20reduce%20the%20risk.%20Google%20is%20updating%20our%20inactivity%20policy%20for%20Google%20Accounts%20to%202%20years%20across%20our%20products.%20Starting%20in%20December%2C%20if%20a%20Google%20account%20has%20not%20been%20used%20or%20signed%20into%20for%20at%20least%202%20years%2C%20we%20may%20delete%20the%20account%20and%20its%20contents%2C%20including%20content%20within%20Google%20Workspace%20(Gmail%2C%20Docs%2C%20Drive%2C%20Meet%2C%20Calendar)%2C%20and%20Google%20Photos.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThis%20is%20because%20forgotten%20or%20unattended%20accounts%20often%20rely%20on%20old%20or%20re-used%20passwords%20that%20may%20have%20been%20compromised%2C%20haven't%20had%20two-factor%20authentication%20set%20up%2C%20and%20receive%20fewer%20security%20checks%20by%20the%20user%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20post%20read.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BOur%20internal%20analysis%20shows%20abandoned%20accounts%20are%20at%20least%2010x%20less%20likely%20than%20active%20accounts%20to%20have%20two-step%20verification%20set%20up.%20These%20accounts%20are%20often%20vulnerable%2C%20and%20once%20an%20account%20is%20compromised%2C%20it%20can%20be%20used%20for%20anything%20from%20identity%20theft%20to%20a%20vector%20for%20unwanted%20or%20even%20malicious%20content%2C%20like%20spam.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWho%20is%20at%20risk%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20policy%20only%20applies%20to%20personal%20Google%20accounts%20that%20haven't%20opened%20their%20Gmail%20account%20in%20two%20years%20and%20will%20not%20affect%20accounts%20for%20organizations%20like%20schools%20or%20businesses.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EHow%20to%20keep%20your%20account%20active%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAccording%20to%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fblog.google%2Ftechnology%2Fsafety-security%2Fupdating-our-inactive-account-policies%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EGoogle%20blog%20post%2C%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20simplest%20way%20to%20keep%20a%20Google%20account%20active%20is%20to%20sign%20in%20at%20least%20once%20every%20two%20years.%20If%20you%20have%20signed%20into%20your%20Google%20Account%20or%20any%20of%20our%20services%20recently%2C%20your%20account%20is%20considered%20active%20and%20will%20not%20be%20deleted.%20Activity%20might%20include%20these%20types%20of%20actions%20you%20take%20when%20you%20sign%20in%20or%20while%20you're%20signed%20in%20to%20your%20Google%20Account%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EReading%20or%20sending%20an%20email%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EUsing%20Google%20Drive%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWatching%20a%20YouTube%20video%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EDownloading%20an%20app%20on%20the%20Google%20Play%20Store%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EUsing%20Google%20Search%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EUsing%20Google%20Sign-in%20to%20sign%20in%20to%20a%20third-party%20app%20or%20service%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20have%20an%20active%20subscription%20linked%20to%20your%20Google%20Account%2C%20such%20as%20Google%20One%2C%20a%20news%20publication%2C%20or%20an%20app%2C%20Google%20will%20take%20into%20account%20this%20ongoing%20account%20activity%2C%20and%20your%20account%20will%20remain%20unaffected.%20Furthermore%2C%20Google%20has%20no%20current%20intentions%20to%20delete%20accounts%20associated%20with%20YouTube%20videos.%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%